java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Comparable<DateInterval>
public enum DateInterval
extends java.lang.Enum<DateInterval>

This is an enumeration of possible levels of details by the generation of dates. Dates have an interval with an lower and an upper bound. But the values in these intervals can be handled in different ways. It is possible to generate dates with only a year, or a year and a month or even a year, a month and a day.

Level of details
Level of details specifies how the generated dates will look like. There're different levels available:
  • year
    • has the lowest level of detail. Only a year in the interval will be generated.
  • month
    • The level of detail is between year and day. The generated date has a year and a month field.
  • day
    • has the highest level of detail. When this level has been chosen, all fields are generated. That is a year, a month and a day.

Example
Suppose you've got the interval of [2007, 2009]. In terms of a date a level of details defines the possible values for this interval.

Year
If the level of detail is set to year then the values will be only the years in the interval.
2007
2008
2009

Month
The available values will be greater if the details of month are enabled. Then we've 36 values.
3 years * 12 month = 36 month (values).
January
...
December

Day
The most details dates are generated by the day level. For each year the days are calculated. That makes 1095 days in the example used above.

Enum Constant Detail

YEAR

public static final DateInterval YEAR
splits the date interval into the number of years

Example
Suppose you have an interval of [2007, 2009]. If you wanna split the given interval only into years the available values would be:
2007
2008
2009

When to use?
Use this option when the dates to generate should only consist of years. The generated time stamp for a facet modified looks like this:
date modified: year

MONTH

public static final DateInterval MONTH
splits the date interval into month. It is medium detailed.

Example
Suppose you've got the interval [2007, 2009]. In terms of a date interval with the detail of month you would get the following values:
January
...
December
The above values depict only the values available once and not for all years, but for one. Of course, you would get the month of all years. In the example here there're three years so 3 * 12 = 36 month. In other words, 36 values are available and it's more detailed as years.

When to use?
Use this approach when a date should be generated with a year and a month. The generated time stamp for a facet modified looks like this:
date modified: month/year

DAY

public static final DateInterval DAY
splits the date interval into days. This is the most detailed way of possible splitting.

Example
Imagine you've the following interval [2007, 2009]. In terms of a date interval and with the details of days you would get for each year in the interval the days.

3 * 365 = 1095 days

In the example above are three years multiplied by 365 days per year makes a total amount of 1095 days as possible values.

When to use?
Use days when you want dates with a year, a month and a day. The generated time stamp for a facet modified looks like this:
date modified: month/day/year
